# Chapter 2. Introduction
## Steps To Use ICExplorer-XTop
### Build Workspace
Build Workspace 
To build workspace and import design data, it needs the following steps.  
	• Create a workspace. 
xtop> create_workspace tutorial  
	• Link reference libraries. 
xtop> link_reference_library -format lef "./lef/turorial.lef"  
	• Import design data. 
	• xtop> define_designs -verilogs netlistFileNames -defs 
defFileNames 
	• xtop> set_site_map  {unit core12T} 
xtop> import_designs  
	• Create corners, modes and scenarios. 
	• xtop> create_corner {slow} 
	• xtop> create_corner {fast} 
	• xtop> create_mode {func} 
	• xtop> create_mode {test} 
	• xtop> create_scenario -corner {slow} -mode {func} {func_slow} 
	• xtop> create_scenario -corner {fast} -mode {func} {func_fast} 
	• xtop> create_scenario -corner {slow} -mode {test} {test_slow} 
xtop> create_scenario -corner {fast} -mode {test} {test_fast}  
	• Link timing libraries. 
	• xtop> link_timing_library -corner {slow} \ 
	•                           -search_type min_max 
{./lib/tutorialwc.idb} 
	• xtop> link_timing_library -corner {fast} \ 
                          -search_type min_max 
{./lib/tutorialbc.idb}  
	• Read timing data files. 
xtop> read_timing_data -data_dir ./sta_data

Parameters

Name
tmlib_table_sample_method --Specify the sample method to get a value representing a table or vector.

Type
type: enum "fon fixed table_center table_average rect_average arbitrary_average"

Default
default = "table_center"

Description
This parameter specifies the sample method to get a value representing a table or a vector. While analyzing
a timing library, it needs to get typical characteristics, like delay, transition, power of a cell. And it is often
to look-up in a 2D table, and needs to assume a working environment for it, such as an input transition,
and a fanout load. It provides four typical sample methods.

--fon. A cell drives 'n' copies of itself recursively. Theoretically, it will reach a stable state soon, and this
is used as the working environment. The special 'n' can be configured by tmlib_fanout_factor.

--fixed. Users need to specify a fixed input transition and a fixed fanout load by tmlib_input_transition
and tmlib_fanout_load.

--table_center. The value on the center of the table will be used. While any dimension is not even number,
and the center contains more than one number, the average of them is used.The center point of table can
be offset by specify a center offset value through tmlib_table_center_offset.

--table_average. The average value of all the points in table is used. The marginal points can be cut off
by specify a excision depth through tmlib_table_excision_depth.

--rect_average. The average value of all the overlapped points between a rectangle and the original table.
The rectangle is specified through tmlib_rect_average_rect.

--arbitrary_average. The average value of all user specified points through
tmlib_arbitrary_average_points. The points are arbitrary and not required to satisfy any shape
requirement.

For cells with clock pins, it also needs to specify a typical transition for the clock through
tmlib_clock_transition. And this is applicable for all the above four methods.

Examples

% set_parameter tmlib_table_sample_method {fixed}
% set_parameter tmlib_input_transition {0.01}
% set_parameter tmlib_clock_transition {0.008}
% set_parameter tmlib_fanout_load {100}

% set_parameter tmlib_table_sample_method {fon}
% set_parameter tmlib_fanout_factor {5}
% set_parameter tmlib_clock_transition {0.008}

% set_parameter tmlib_table_sample_method {table_average}
% set_parameter tmlib_table_excision_depth {2}

% set_parameter tmlib_table_sample_method {table_center}
% set_parameter tmlib_table_center_offset {(1,2)}

% set_parameter tmlib_table_sample_method {rect_average}
% set_parameter tmlib_rect_average_rect {((1, 1) (4, 4))}

% set_parameter tmlib_table_sample_method {arbitrary_average}  
% set_parameter tmlib_arbitrary_average_points {(1,1) (3,3) (5,5)}


